    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1961-04-18T15:23:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1961-04-18T15:23:00-05:00" n="124"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d124">
                <head>124. Telegram From the Chief of Naval Operations (<persName corresp="#p_BAAA1"
                        type="from">Burke</persName>) to the Commander in Chief, Atlantic (<persName
                        corresp="#p_DARL1" type="to">Dennison</persName>)<note n="0" type="source"
                        xml:id="d124fn0">Source: Naval Historical Center, Area Files, Bumpy Road
                        Materials. Top Secret; Limited Distribution. A “chronology of events on Cuba
                        taken from the records in Op-00 immediate office” indicates that this
                        message was sent as a back channel message. (Ibid.)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1961-04-18T15:23:00-05:00">April 18, 1961, 3:23 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>182023Z. Exclusive for Adm <persName corresp="#p_DARL1">Dennison</persName> and
                    RAdm <persName corresp="#p_CRAJE1">Clark</persName> from <persName
                        corresp="#p_BAAA1">Burke</persName>. There is little information here on
                    status of operation. Few reports available indicate operation may be in
                    desperate straits. No general uprising in Cuba yet.</p>
                <p>What is most urgently needed here is information on which to make an assessment
                    of the situation or a judgment on what to do at high levels.</p>
                <p>Following questions at high-level conference were asked: <list>
                        <label>A.</label>
                        <item>Can anti-<persName corresp="#p_CRF1">Castro</persName> forces go into
                            bush as guerillas?</item>
                        <label>B.</label>
                        <item>Could anti-<persName corresp="#p_CRF1">Castro</persName> forces be
                            evacuated from beach by unmarked United States <gloss
                                target="#t_amphib1">amphib</gloss> boats?</item>
                        <label>C.</label>
                        <item>Is there a possibility that anti-<persName corresp="#p_CRF1"
                                >Castro</persName> forces can break through?</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Following possible United States actions were discussed:<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d124fn1">In his initial draft of this message <persName
                            corresp="#p_BAAA1">Burke</persName> wrote: “Nobody here wants to commit
                        United States forces to bail out this affair, but if situation is as bad as
                        reported something may have to be done.” (Ibid.)</note>
                    <list>
                        <label>A.</label>
                        <item>Unmarked Naval aircraft fly cover over beach area to protect
                                anti-<persName corresp="#p_CRF1">Castro</persName> forces from air
                            attack.</item>
                        <label>B.</label>
                        <item>Unmarked Naval aircraft destroy <persName corresp="#p_CRF1"
                                >Castro</persName> tanks.</item>
                        <label>C.</label>
                        <item>Unmarked Naval aircraft furnish close air support.</item>
                        <label>D.</label>
                        <item>Unmarked <gloss target="#t_amphib1">amphib</gloss> boats from United
                            States evacuate anti-<persName corresp="#p_CRF1">Castro</persName>
                            forces from beach.</item>
                        <label>E.</label>
                        <item>Land experienced Marines by either helicopter or boat to assess
                            situation and give judgment on what to do.</item>
                        <label>F.</label>
                        <item>Large air drops by United States Air Force aircraft to anti-<persName
                                corresp="#p_CRF1">Castro</persName> forces.</item>
                        <label>G.</label>
                        <item>Danger in all above actions of United States involvement. No decision
                            was made to do any of these but air drop. The same subjects may be
                            discussed later.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
            </div>
        </body>
